        "text": "I came across Laws of Form a decade even earlier (the 1970s), guided by Stewart Brand’s review and Heinz vonFoerster’s commentary in The Whole Earth Catalog. At that time I was building a home in the forests of Hawaii, and had plenty of time to think about abstraction as I hauled lumber up a hill and pounded 200,000 nails to hold it all together. The unary logic in Laws of Form abandons Truth to Existence, a position that seemed quite reasonable to someone who was living in a forest. One day my mother showed up with a copy of Laws of Form, saying that she understood nothing inside, but it had literally jumped off the bookstore shelf as she passed by and landed at her feet. She thought it looked like something I might find interesting. Turns out, I’d been reflecting upon Crossing and Calling without the text for over a year. And I knew not to ignore Jungian synchronicity."
